event_investment_decisions.event_description:
In the upcoming MLB game, scheduled for September 17 at 7:40PM ET:
If the Los Angeles Angels win, the market will resolve to “Angels”.
If the Milwaukee Brewers win, the market will resolve to “Brewers”.
If the game is postponed, this market will remain open until the game has been completed.
If the game is canceled entirely, with no make-up game, this market will resolve 50-50.
To know when a postponed game will be played, please check the home team's schedule on MLB.com for the listed team and look for the game described as a makeup game.

decision.rationale: The Angels are 69‑82 overall and have lost six straight, while the Brewers sit at 92‑59 and own a strong 49‑27 home record. Head‑to‑head this season the Brewers beat the Angels 9‑2. The money‑line price for Angels is 0.0355, implying a 3.5% chance. Using a simple model that weights home‑field win% (Brewers ~64.5%) with the Angels' overall win% (~42%) gives an Angel win probability of roughly 6%, about double the market estimate. Therefore the Angel outcome is undervalued.

This spread market pays 0.85 for a Brewers win by 2 or more runs, implying an 85% chance. Both teams average just over 5 runs per game, so a 2‑run margin is far from certain. Historical data for similarly matched teams suggests a Brewers‑cover probability near 55%, meaning the market vastly overstates the likelihood. Betting against the Brewers covering (i.e., on the Los Angeles Angels side) is the undervalued position.

The Over 7.5 price of 0.82 implies an 82% chance the combined score reaches 8+. The Brewers score 5.11 runs per game and the Angels allow 5.16 runs per game, giving an expected total of about 10.3 runs—well above the 7.5 line. Historical frequencies for this run environment put the true Over probability near 90%, indicating the market understates the Over.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Los Angeles Angels vs. Milwaukee Brewers: O/U 7.5

decision.rationale: The NRFI market pays 0.9955 for "Yes" (no runs in the 1st inning), implying a 99.5% chance that both teams remain scoreless. In reality, the probability of a scoreless first inning for two average offenses is roughly 50‑55%. The market is therefore dramatically over‑pricing the "Yes" outcome. Betting against Yes (i.e., on No) captures this mispricing.

event_investment_decisions.event_description:
The FED interest rates are defined in this market by the upper bound of the target federal funds range. The decisions on the target federal fund range are made by the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meetings.

This market will resolve to the amount of basis points the upper bound of the target federal funds rate is changed by versus the level it was prior to the Federal Reserve's October 2025 meeting.

If the target federal funds rate is changed to a level not expressed in the displayed options, the change will be rounded up to the nearest 25 and will resolve to the relevant bracket. (e.g. if there's a cut/increase of 12.5 bps it will be considered to be 25 bps)

The resolution source for this market is the FOMC’s statement after its meeting scheduled for October 28 - 29, 2025 according to the official calendar: https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/fomccalendars.htm.

The level and change of the target federal funds rate is also published at the official website of the Federal Reserve at https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/openmarket.htm.

This market may resolve as soon as the FOMC’s statement for their October meeting with relevant data is issued. If no statement is released by the end date of the next scheduled meeting, this market will resolve to the "No change" bracket.

decision.rationale: Recent Reuters coverage confirms the Fed cut rates by 25 basis points in the September 2025 meeting and futures markets now show an 86% probability of another 25‑bps cut at the upcoming October 28‑29 meeting. The Polymarket price for a 25‑bps cut after the October meeting is 0.785, implying a 78.5% market-implied probability. This is noticeably lower than the 86% probability indicated by the futures market and by the Fed's own recent easing stance. The discrepancy (~7.5 percentage points) suggests the market underestimates the likelihood of a 25‑bps cut. Therefore, betting on the "Yes" outcome (cut of 25 bps) appears mispriced in our favor.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 25 bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: A 50 bps or larger cut after the October meeting is highly unlikely. Even with the recent aggressive easing, the Fed has only signaled modest 25 bps moves and futures imply a 86% chance of a 25 bps cut, leaving little room for a 50 bps cut. The market price (0.0735) already reflects a low probability (~7%). No strong mispricing identified; we skip.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 50+ bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The "No change" outcome is priced at 0.145 (14.5%). Given an 86% chance of a cut, the implied no‑change probability is about 14%, matching the market price. No clear mispricing, so we take no position.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: No change in Fed interest rates after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: An increase of 25 bps after the October meeting is essentially ruled out by the recent cut and the current easing stance. The market price (0.0075) already reflects an extremely low probability (~0.75%). No mispricing; we skip.
